      "title": "Sudan: Why a shift out out of Famine (IPC Phase 5) may not equate to recovery",
      "rawText": "Sudan: Why a shift out out of Famine (IPC Phase 5) may not equate to recovery A shift from Famine (IPC Phase 5) to Emergency (IPC Phase 4) reflects that the technical thresholds that define Famine (IPC Phase 5) are no longer met under current evidence, and conditions do not decisively indicate a return to Famine (IPC Phase 5) as the most likely outcome. However, in Sudan's current conflict context, this shift may not necessarily imply substantive recovery. Rather, it may reflect the effects of prior widespread mortality, the fluidity of population movement, or short-term fluctuations in access to food. The underlying drivers remain severe, and the risk of reentry into Famine (IPC Phase 5) remains plausible. Famine (IPC Phase 5) thresholds. Under the Integrated Acute Food Insecurity Phase Classification (IPC) scale, Famine (Phase 5) is classified when evidence is substantial enough to infer that all three of the following thresholds are met in a defined area: 1) at least 20 percent of households face an extreme lack of food after employing all available coping; 2) the Global Acute Malnutrition prevalence among children under 5 reaches or exceeds 30 percent (measured by weight-for-height z-score) or 15 percent (measured by mid-upper-arm circumference); and 3) the Crude Death Rate exceeds 2 deaths per 10,000 people per day. Why classifications can shift. In Sudan’s conflict environment, changes in food security classifications may reflect changes in factors that influence indicators and information but do not reflect meaningful improvements in food security. Several factors can drive these shifts, highlighting why an Emergency (IPC Phase 4) designation does not automatically signal recovery. The effects of widespread mortality. A Famine, by definition, results in widespread death. These deaths ultimately impact future mortality rates once a large share of the most-at-risk population has died. This tragic dynamic does not indicate recovery; it reflects irreversible loss of life and changes in the composition of the surviving population. Population displacement. Large-scale displacement can substantially influence measured outcomes. Households may flee from one area to another, altering the relative concentration of people who are malnourished or at heightened risk of mortality in specific geographic areas over time. For example, an area classified in Famine may experience changes in conflict dynamics that prompt widespread displacement. While the total number of people at risk of death may remain unchanged, their departure from the area can mean that Famine is no longer observed in the original area. Whether Famine emerges in the new receiving area depends on the size of the incoming population relative to the host community and on whether their combined levels of hunger, acute malnutrition, and mortality meet the Famine thresholds. Short-term fluctuations. Some factors that impact food security may change periodically, such as infrequent injections of humanitarian assistance, seasonal improvements to food availability, and short-lived market inflows. These factors may slightly improve some indicators without resolving the deeper causes that put the population at repeated risk of hunger-related mortality, namely market collapse, livelihood destruction, asset depletion, and repeated displacement. Certain factors may lead to short-term improvements, especially when combined with the impact of earlier mortality on the composition of the surviving population, yet the risk remains that the Famine (IPC Phase 5) thresholds could be met again. Shifts in information access. Insecurity and access constraints can hinder evidence collection and reduce visibility in the most severely affected areas. Notably, data collection is complicated by the fact that populations move in search of safety and food, a factor which also shifts where mortality is concentrated. This does not equate to overall better outcomes. Although FEWS NET assigns the most likely IPC Phase irrespective of information gaps, changes in information availability nonetheless alter the body of evidence analysts rely on. A shift from Famine (IPC Phase 5) to Emergency (IPC Phase 4) does not necessarily indicate sustained recovery or improvement. This additional information is provided to highlight that the situation in Sudan is currently highly complex. The difference between Emergency (IPC Phase 4) and Famine (IPC Phase 5) reflects whether measurable outcomes have crossed specific numerical thresholds indicative of Famine (IPC Phase 5). Populations in an area where outcomes sit just below the Famine (IPC Phase 5) thresholds are still facing widespread hunger-related malnutrition and mortality. Small deteriorations in access, displacement, or food assistance levels could push outcomes across the Famine (IPC Phase 5) threshold once again. The underlying drivers remain severe, and the risk of reentry into Famine (IPC Phase 5) remains plausible. hwellman@fews.net Tue, 03/10/2026 - 18:56 Download the report 652",
